ne1><gtr:line2>Capital Park</gtr:line2><gtr:postCode>CB21 5XB</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_FUNDER</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/D1666577-C31B-4F99-A894-5A3B0A4628AE"><gtr:id>D1666577-C31B-4F99-A894-5A3B0A4628AE</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Deborah</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Halliday</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-173-27-0106"><gtr:id>19DC56B4-A16C-45BE-9E37-73A072D707B0</gtr:id><gtr:title>Developing a Research Framework to Underpin the Productive Ward Programme</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0106</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The Productive Ward programme has been piloted in acute hospitals by the NHS Institute for Innovation and Improvement, and is proposed as a useful tool to raise the safety and quality of care for patients. It has been implemented in some Trusts in the East of England without a strong evidence base to support its effectiveness. The need to assess the current situation and develop a research framework to underpin its expansion has been identified.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;The main aims are: &lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>To identify staff, stakeholders and patients views to determine areas of benefit from the Programme&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>To identify gaps in the evidence base for the Programme&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>To identify further research questions to support the Programmes full implementation&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>A mixed-methods approach will be adopted. The first stage will consist of a scoping exercise, including in-depth interviews and a documentary analysis of Trust policies and ward procedures.&amp;nbsp; The next stage will be to undertake a literature review to determine where there is strong evidence and gaps in evidence for the Programme's effectiveness. Strong evidence will be disseminated and monitored to promote adoption. Where the evidence base is weaker, research questions will be developed to further inform the evidence base. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>75605</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">RES-173-27-0106</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-173-27-0106</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530-BA5E-562216587E68</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Sociology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530-BA5E-562216587E68</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Sociology</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes